2026-04-16 12:17:16 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Load module internal wiring between diode cathode and both lamp positive terminals'] hypothesis_explanation='The PSU LED is on and Control Module 1’s series path is correctly wired with no polarity inversion, so 12V is available on the line. All control-module indicators being absent only explains lack of LED indication, not the main lamp fault. Observation of the load module shows that the input positive cable goes to the diode anode, but the diode cathode is not connected to anything, and both lamps’ positive terminals have no cable attached. Their negatives are correctly tied to the return line and continuity of the lamps themselves is good. This leaves an open circuit on the positive side to the load, so no current can flow through either lamp regardless of the upstream state. The root cause is therefore a wiring/open-circuit fault inside the load module: the diode cathode (output) is not connected to the positive terminals of the main lamp and indicator lamp. Restoring/rewiring this connection should restore operation of the load and its indicator when 12V is applied with correct polarity.'
